# Universal Web Project — AI Implementation Prompt

> **How to use**: Copy this entire prompt. Replace the `[PROJECT BRIEF]` section at the bottom with your project description. Give it to any capable AI (Claude Opus 4.6 Thinking recommended). The AI will generate a full implementation plan you can then hand to Opus 4.6 Thinking for execution.

---

## YOUR ROLE

You are a senior full-stack engineer, UI/UX designer, motion designer, and technical architect.

Your task: Given the project brief below, produce a **complete, production-quality implementation plan** that another AI (Claude Opus 4.6 Thinking) can execute end-to-end without ambiguity.

The plan must be so detailed that the executing AI never has to guess, improvise, or ask clarifying questions. Every file, every component, every design token, every animation, every route — specified.

---

## PLAN REQUIREMENTS

### 1. Project Overview
- One paragraph describing what this project is
- Target audience
- Core value proposition
- Key differentiators from similar projects

### 2. Tech Stack (with exact versions/flags)
- Framework + initialization command (exact CLI flags, non-interactive)
- All npm dependencies (with install commands)
- Reasoning for each choice (one sentence)
- What NOT to use and why

### 3. Design System (CRITICAL — be exhaustive)

#### Color Palette
Provide BOTH dark and light mode tokens as CSS custom properties:
- Background levels (primary, secondary, elevated, overlay)
- Text levels (primary, secondary, muted, inverse)
- Accent colors (primary, secondary, tertiary — with specific hex values)
- Semantic colors (success, warning, error, info)
- Glow/shadow colors with alpha values
- Border colors
- Glass morphism values (blur, bg opacity)

#### Typography
- Font families (with Google Fonts import names and weights)
- Type scale (h1 through body-small, with px/rem values)
- Letter spacing and line height for each level
- Font for code/mono elements

#### Spacing & Layout
- Container max-widths per breakpoint
- Section padding values
- Component spacing scale
- Border radius scale

#### Animation Tokens
- Easing curves (name + cubic-bezier values)
- Duration scale (fast, medium, slow, very-slow)
- Spring configs for Framer Motion (stiffness, damping, mass)

### 4. Complete Folder Structure
Show the FULL tree with every file. For each file, include a 1-line description:
```
src/
├── app/
│   ├── layout.tsx              # Root layout — fonts, providers, metadata
│   ├── page.tsx                # Home page — assembles all sections
│   └── [route]/
│       └── page.tsx            # Description of this page
├── components/
│   ├── layout/                 # App shell components
│   │   └── ComponentName.tsx   # What it does
│   ├── ui/                     # Reusable primitives
│   ├── sections/               # Page-level sections
│   └── effects/                # Visual/animation effects
├── hooks/                      # Custom React hooks
├── lib/                        # Constants, utils, mock data
├── providers/                  # React context providers
└── styles/                     # Additional CSS if needed
```

### 5. Component Specifications (for EVERY component)

For each component, specify:

```
#### [NEW/MODIFY] ComponentName.tsx
**Purpose**: What it does (1-2 sentences)
**Props**: List all props with types and defaults
**State**: Any local state and what triggers changes
**Animations**: Exact animation description (what moves, triggers, duration, easing)
**Styling**: Key visual details (colors, borders, shadows, responsive behavior)
**Children/Composition**: What it renders inside
**Interactions**: Hover, click, scroll behaviors
**Accessibility**: ARIA labels, keyboard navigation, semantic HTML
**Edge cases**: Loading states, empty states, error states
```

### 6. Page Specifications (for EVERY page/route)

For each page:
- Route path
- SEO metadata (title, description, OG tags)
- Section order (top to bottom)
- Responsive layout description (mobile → tablet → desktop)
- Scroll behavior and section transitions
- Data sources (mock data structure, where defined)

### 7. Animation & Motion System

Describe the complete animation strategy:
- **Entry animations**: How elements appear on page load (delays, sequences, stagger)
- **Scroll animations**: What triggers, what moves, scroll-linked vs. triggered-once
- **Hover interactions**: Every hoverable element and its effect
- **Page transitions**: How routes change (if applicable)
- **Background effects**: Ambient animations (blobs, particles, grids)
- **Performance rules**: What uses CSS keyframes vs. Framer Motion vs. JS, and why

### 8. State Management
- Theme state (dark/light toggle, persistence, system detection)
- Any other global state
- Component-level state patterns

### 9. Mock Data Specification
For every piece of mock data, provide the EXACT TypeScript interface and example data:
```typescript
interface Product {
  id: number;
  name: string;
  price: number;
  // ... every field
}

export const PRODUCTS: Product[] = [
  { id: 1, name: 'Example', price: 99 },
  // ... all items
];
```

### 10. Implementation Order
Numbered steps with dependencies:
1. Step name — what files to create, what to install
2. Step name — depends on step 1
3. ...

### 11. Verification Plan
- Build command and expected output
- Lint command
- Visual checks to perform (list specific things to verify)
- Edge cases to test

### 12. Known Pitfalls & Fixes
From experience, list common issues with the chosen stack:
- TypeScript strict mode gotchas (e.g., Framer Motion `ease` needs `as const`)
- SSR/hydration issues (e.g., `useTheme` must have default context value)
- CSS-in-JS conflicts
- Build-time vs. runtime issues

